Prologue
"Please!" Queen Elven pleaded, "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with royal advisors standing by. The queen had given birth to a girl. Just thinking about it made the Ice King furrow his brow.
The infant girl looked just like her mother: pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, with a few strands of blue hair. The Ice King thought having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, before this, he had only sons.
"You have two choices, either kill this child or leave her in the wilderness. Elven, this is your punishment." He said her name with malice, as if it were poison. He always did.
The Land of Frost was not always a kingdom. It was once divided into two parts, northern and southern. The north established a non-magical kingdom, while the south was a kingdom filled with magical power. Due to the north's greed, the two kingdoms waged endless wars until the south proposed a ceasefire.
The southern kingdom had already fallen into despair, and the royal family was willing to do anything to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed to marry their only princess to the north, making her the queen of the north and bearing a son who would become the future king. Afterwards, the south would merge with the north, establishing a unified kingdom. The north accepted this proposal, and thus Princess Elwin married Prince Acul.
"Please, my king, for the safety of my child, you can do anything to me—imprison me, exile me, or even kill me." Queen Elwin pleaded, holding her child tightly in her arms.
King of Ice looked down at the queen, filled with hatred. Perhaps, just perhaps, he would feel a bit of pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, caring for him during his most desolate moments and giving him children.
"Alright. The child can live in the palace." Hearing the king's words, the queen let out a sigh of relief. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
Both the royal advisor and Queen Elwin showed expressions of terror. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. "As you command, my king." She bowed her head.
The Ice King ordered the royal adviser to bring the Queen's daughter to an empty room in Elvin's palace. After that, he commanded the guards to take Elvin to the public execution ground where all citizens could see.
When the guards led her to the execution ground, the citizens saw their only queen—who was also the kindest queen—about to be executed, and they felt very angry. Some people cried, some shouted and tried to attack the guards, and some wanted to know why this was happening; but they all had the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
When Elvin approached the wooden pole, the most terrifying person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner for the burning punishment. Elvin, the former queen, would be burned alive. No one should be subjected to burning, even criminals. In the Frost Kingdom, burning was the cruelest punishment.
Alvin was tied to a wooden post, and the king began to tell how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Frost Kingdom refused to believe and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the wooden post, and a tear rolled down the former queen's face.
"Carly, live on!" The life of Queen Alvin came to an end.
Silence reigned in the hall.
In the south wing of this cold palace, an endless "ticking" sound came from the room on the far left. Past servants had always been curious about what was inside the room, yet they were too afraid to approach. The maids walked around the hall, whispering to each other and spreading all sorts of rumors. Some believed that Queen Alvin, the late wife of the Ice King, was living in this room, waiting to be released.
They were very wrong. Avery thought, as he walked toward the south wing. The servants walked back and forth along the walls, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there are also many rumors about TA, because TA is the only person allowed to enter the room.
Knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you inside?" Avery whispered to this complicated door, decorated with snowflakes and crowns, symbols of royalty.
TA didn't know if she would really let him in this time, which was different from before. I still had bruises from last time. Avery recalled this and couldn't help but laughed. At that time, Carly threw a book at him, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A light sound came from inside the room, as if saying she couldn't go anywhere, just stay there.
"May I come in?" Avery asked, TA couldn't forget the consequences of entering uninvited last time.
A light sound came from the room again. It seemed to say, "Come in." Avery felt a chill, unsure whether it was from the cold or the sound. Although TA had been there for many years, Avery still found it a bit strange to hear a voice coming from the room.
"I'm coming in." Avery said, slowly opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual by normal standards, but it was expected. Papers were everywhere in the room. Books were scattered on the floor, the table was broken, and there were many ice sculptures in the room. There were no windows and almost no light. It was also colder than other parts of the palace (which indicated many problems). The room looked as if it had been hit by a blizzard, everything was in chaos.
The girl in the room was curled up in bed, covered with blankets, reading a notebook. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Avery asked, sitting by Carly's bed.
